<DATE>940308
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / World Stock Markets (America): Arms groups' Dollars 1.9bn
merger helps lift Dow
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
Rallying European stocks, firmer bond prices and news of a billion-dollar
defence industry merger lifted US share prices across the board yesterday,
writes Patrick Harverson in New York.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 23.92 ahead at 3,856.22, slightly
below the high for the day. The Standard &amp; Poor's 500 gained 2.17 at 466.91,
while the American SE composite was 2.59 higher at 469.06 and the Nasdaq
composite up 4.50 at 795.05. New York SE volume was 285.6m shares.
After recent wild fluctuations, equity prices opened the new week in
impressive fashion, moving into positive territory right from the opening.
Traders said several factors were behind the advance: a recovery in European
stocks, hit last week by turmoil in local bond markets; gains in US bond
prices; and news of a big merger between defence companies.
The latter was particularly welcome, given that the market had been rattled
by the collapse two weeks ago of the billion-dollar union between Bell
Atlantic and Tele-Communications. Yesterday's news involved Grumman, the
Long Island defence contractor, which has agreed to be taken over by Martin
Marietta, another defence group, in a deal valued at Dollars 1.9bn.
The announcement of the agreement sent Grumman's shares soaring in heavy
dealings. By the close they were trading at Dollars 54 1/8 , up Dollars 14
1/4 , or 36 per cent. Martin Marietta has offered to pay Dollars 55 each for
every Grumman share. Wall Street clearly liked the deal, because Martin
Marietta's shares also rose on the news, climbing Dollars 1 1/4 to Dollars
46.
Salomon advanced Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 51 3/8 as investors reacted warmly
to Friday's late announcement that Mr Warren Buffett, the billionaire
investor and former interim chairman of the securities house, had increased
his stake in the company from 14.7 per cent to 19 per cent. The move was
seen as a vote of confidence in Salomon's long term ability to generate
profits.
USAir dropped Dollars 1 1/8 to Dollars 9, a 52-week low, in busy trading
after warning that it would make a pre-tax loss of Dollars 200m in the first
quarter of the year, against a deficit of Dollars 61m a year earlier. The
airline blamed bad weather and price competition for its poor earnings.
Philip Morris, which has been hit recently by concern that the government
might impose strict regulations on cigarettes, rose Dollars 1 7/8 to Dollars
56 3/4 amid speculation that the planned increase in excise taxes may be
smaller than originally feared.
Brazil
Heavy trading took Brazil 7.1 per cent higher by the close on expectations
that the government would not raise taxes on foreign investment and amid
optimism on constitutional reform. The Bovespa index was finally 799 points
ahead at 11,939. Turnover came to Cr216.1bn (Dollars 314.1m).
Trading picked up amid reports of proposals to end all state monopolies.
Canada
Toronto closed solidly higher after fairly active trading, with most sectors
posting gains as fears of an imminent rise in US interest rates appeared to
ease.
The TSE 300 index rose 38.1 to 4,436.6 and advances led declines by 472 to
313 after volume of 69.6m shares.
</TEXT>
