<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / International Company News: Westinghouse warns of
first-quarter earnings dip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Westinghouse Electric, the US conglomerate, issued a profits warning last
night, confirming recent comments by chairman and chief executive Michael
Jordan that the company would perform worse in the first quarter of 1994
than a year before.
In a statement after the market closed, Mr Jordan said earnings per share
for the period were likely to be 10 cents, down from 14 cents in the first
three months of 1993. Higher pension costs and a lower income from licensees
were behind the fall, along with a one-time gain from the sale of two radio
stations in 1993. Operating profits for the period would be down 10 per
cent, he added.
</TEXT>
