<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / International Company News: Goldman Sachs profit estimated
at Dollars 2.7bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Goldman Sachs, the private US investment bank, earned a pre-tax profit of
Dollars 2.7bn last year, according to an industry newsletter. The firm is
believed to have earned Dollars 1.5bn before taxes in 1992.
The firm would not officially comment on the figures, which were obtained by
Investment Dealers' Digest from a prospectus for a recent Goldman Eurobond
offering, but sources close to the firm say they are accurate. The data
confirms that Goldman is the most profitable firm on Wall Street, and its
150 partners, who share a good deal of the profits, are the most highly
rewarded professionals in the business.
However, last year may prove to have been the peak in the earnings cycle for
both Goldman and Wall Street. Since US short-term interest rates were
increased by the Federal Reserve on February 4, US and European financial
markets have been in turmoil, exposing some of the biggest players in the
capital markets to substantial trading losses.
Goldman is rumoured to have incurred large short-term losses, although the
firm insists its operations are profitable for the year. Over the longer
term, rising interest rates will make it harder for investment banks to
match the extraordinary profits earned between 1990 and 1993, when US
interest rates declined to record lows.
According to the IDD figures, Goldman's revenues in 1993 totalled Dollars
13.2bn, up from Dollars 9bn the year before. That makes the firm's profit
margin 20.1 per cent, which analysts say is the best among large Wall Street
investment banks. The record-breaking year lifted Goldman's capital to
Dollars 5bn from Dollars 3.7bn.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Goldman Sachs Group Limited Partnership.
</CO>
<XX>
