<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / International Company News: ANA posts first loss for 22
years and cuts payout
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO and PAUL ABRAHAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
All Nippon Airways (ANA) yesterday said it would post a loss for the year
ending this month - its first loss for 22 years - and cut its dividend.
The Japanese carrier, hit by the continuing weak demand, expects a pre-tax
loss of Y3bn (Dollars 28m), compared with a previously forecast pre-tax
profit of Y6bn.
Operating profits are revised down to Y769bn from an earlier forecast of
Y782bn. The dividend is to be reduced to Y3 a share from the Y4 paid for
1992-93 when pre-tax profits totalled Y13.3bn.
The airline said international and domestic businesses were down nearly 3
per cent, but it had been hurt most by the slump in the domestic market.
Greater deregulation had enabled rival JAL to eat into the domestic market,
ANA's stronghold, while the airline faced growing competition from other
forms of transportation, such as fast-speed rail.
Competition on international routes, where ANA has been building its
presence since 1986, was fierce in the face of the spreading popularity of
discount air fares.
ANA's gloomy outlook reflects the pressures on Japanese airlines, which have
been struggling to maintain profitability after a slowdown in air travel and
increased competition from lower cost foreign airlines on international
routes.
In particular, the high costs of financing airports and airport development
have been a large burden on Japanese airlines, which face some of the
highest personnel costs in the world.
ANA faces paying a high price for its ambitious expansion plans in the late
1980s, when Japan's economic prosperity seemed everlasting.
In a reversal of those years, ANA, in common with other airlines, has been
restructuring to achieve profits with lower growth.
Japanese employment practice makes it difficult to make large cuts in costs
through wide-scale redundancies. Instead, it is scaling back unprofitable
routes and reducing maintenance costs. Capital investment in hotels and
airport facilities is being cut back. The company was forced to sell
aircraft in order to raise cash last year and may have to repeat that
exercise this year.
</TEXT>
<XX>
