<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Badgerline more than doubles to Pounds 6.9m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Badgerline Group, the Avon-based bus company, yesterday reported profits
broadly in line with the forecast made when it came to the market in
November.
The group's shares, floated at 115p, closed 5 1/2 p higher at 125 1/2 p.
The year to end-December saw pre-tax profits more than double to Pounds 6.9m
(Pounds 3.2m) from a turnover Pounds 5m higher at Pounds 132m.
Mr Trevor Smallwood, executive chairman, said all the group's operating
companies had performed well.
He expected last month's Pounds 23m acquisition of PMT Group, the
Staffordshire-based bus company, to be earnings enhancing. The purchase
pushed Badgerline's gearing above 150 per cent, but this was expected to be
reduced significantly by cashflow during the current year.
The group said a recent Office of Fair Trading report into the activities of
its Thamesway subsidiary at Southend had cleared the company of
anti-competitive practices. Its main competitor in the town had been sold by
the local council, which would stabilise the market.
Thamesway had made a meaningful contribution as a result of improved trading
conditions in the Southend area in the second half of the year, and
full-year benefits were expected to continue into 1994.
Badgerline expects a decision soon on the public inquiry concerning its
Kensington depot in Bath, where Safeway wants to build a supermarket. Should
the planning application be blocked, Badgerline would write down the depot's
value in its balance sheet by Pounds 5.2m.
If the plan goes ahead, the group will relocate to a new depot and gain
Pounds 7.5m in free cashflow.
Mr Smallwood said that while it was too early to make any predictions about
trading during the current year, he was satisfied that the policies
Badgerline had pursued would enable the group to continue the progress of
the past few years.
Earnings per share rose to 8.6p (4.1p) compared with the prospectus forecast
of 7.9p.
The group said it would start paying dividends in the current year. Had it
been listed from the beginning of last year, the board would have
recommended a notional net dividend of 4.1p.
</TEXT>
