<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / UK Company News: BBA restructures management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBA, the engineering and motor components group, yesterday unveiled a new
management structure aimed at returning the company to profit.
For the year to December 31 BBA swung from profits of Pounds 47.4m to
pre-tax losses of Pounds 12.8m.
The diversified group has reorganised its businesses into three divisions
comprising automotive activities, aviation services in the US, and a single
industrial and engineering unit.
The scheme has been implemented by Mr Roberto Quarta, chief executive, in an
attempt to refocus the company on core activities and to identify peripheral
activities for disposal.
In the 12 months to end-December, that strategy contributed to a Pounds
17.8m exceptional loss on plant closures and disposals - most notably on the
closure of its friction materials plant in Belgium.
The group also wrote off a Pounds 3.8m investment in United Industries, the
precision tools and springs manufacturer, in which it has a 21.23 per cent
stake.
The exceptional provisions were offset only by an Pounds 18.4m gain on the
sale of Pacific BBA, its partly owned Australian subsidiary.
Mr Peter Clappison, finance director, said the disposals - including the
Pounds 25m sale of three business since the year end - were part of an
on-going restructuring programme which would enable BBA to exploit any
revival in its core businesses.
He warned, however, that there were few signs that such a revival was
underway.
In the automotive division, for example, operating profits fell to Pounds
21.5m (Pounds 37.6m) on sales down 7.6 per cent at Pounds 574.1m.
'There's been extreme price pressure in continental Europe, and we
anticipate a further 10 per decline in volume output next year,' Mr
Clappison added.
Profit margins in the division fell to 1.5 per cent in the second half of
last year, compared with 5.6 per cent in the same period of 1992.
Initial signs, meanwhile, of a recovery in the aviation business were
undermined by 'extreme overcapacity and reduced demand in the US airline
maintenance market'.
Its second half margins also fell sharply, down to 1.6 per cent from 4.2 per
cent in the last six months of 1992.
The performance of the two divisions was offset by an improvement in the
industrial and engineering division, which enjoyed a 42 per cent increase in
operating profits to Pounds 55.3m.
</TEXT>
