<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / UK Company News: Wembley sells 50% of Pacer Cats in Pounds
17m deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Wembley, the leisure group which owns the national stadium, is selling a 50
per cent stake in Pacer Cats, its computer ticketing subsidiary, in a bid to
comply with a banking deadline to cut borrowings by Pounds 40m, writes Tim
Burt.
Ticketmaster, the US computerised ticketing service, is paying Pounds 11m
cash for the stake and will be forming a joint venture to develop the
company. Sir Brian Wolfson, Wembley chairman, said the joint venture would
assume Pounds 6m of Pacer Cats' debt. 'The transaction is worth Pounds 17m
to Wembley and brings us close to the Pounds 40m demanded by our lenders.
The banks are very comfortable with the position.'
The sale follows the disposal of several assets last year, including
National Leisure Catering, Yankee Doodle, another catering group, and the
Needles Hotel.
It is understood the disposal programme is now within 5 per cent of the
total repayments due by March 31.
Although the moves will significantly reduce Wembley's net debt, put at
Pounds 139m at the interim stage last year, lenders, led by Barclays, have
also demanded repayment of a further Pounds 10m by the end of the year.
