<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / USAir warns of deepening losses in low-cost battle: The
biggest test of British Airways' international strategy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS and RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
USAir, the beleaguered US carrier in which British Airways holds a 24.6 per
cent stake, yesterday shocked the airline industry by announcing that
competition from low-cost carriers would drive it even more heavily into
losses this year.
Analysts had been looking for a recovery after five years of losses. But
USAir said pre-tax losses in the first quarter alone were likely to rise
from Dollars 61m to Dollars 200m (Pounds 137m), while for the year as a
whole the deficit was expected to be even worse than last year's Dollars
349m.
USAir confirmed that BA would not invest any more money in the airline until
it was clear that an effective cost-reduction programme was in place and the
company's financial performance improved.
Late last night the company said it had asked its four labour unions to
begin 'substantive talks' on cost cutting and productivity improvements as
part of a plan to return USAir to profit. The plan is expected to involve
drastic cuts in jobs, wages and conditions of employment.
USAir shares tumbled Dollars 1 1/8 to close at Dollars 9.
Mr Seth Schofield, the airline's chairman, president and chief executive,
said one reason for the first-quarter loss was that unusually severe winter
weather in the north-east - USAir's main market - had forced it to cancel
about 8 per cent of its flights in January and February.
But the main reason for the company's grim financial outlook, Mr Schofield
said, was USAir's need to cut fares in response to the steady expansion of
low-cost carriers in many of its east coast markets.
Last month USAir said it was cutting business fares indefinitely by up to 50
per cent on routes between 96 cities in the eastern US. The move was in
response to competition from Southwest Airlines and Continental Airlines,
two low-cost carriers which have begun to make significant inroads into its
markets.
Other large US carriers have responded to low-cost competition by cutting
jobs and increasing productivity, so enabling them to match competitors'
fares without worsening their financial performance. But USAir has so far
made little progress in reducing costs, so lower fares will translate into
bigger losses.
BA has invested nearly Dollars 400m in USAir and was due to invest another
Dollars 450m between now and 1998. But yesterday it said it would not commit
any more funds 'until the outcome of the restructuring is known.'
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
