<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In Assignment Julian Pettifer reports on the trade disputes between Japan
and the US which are damaging relations between the two economic super
powers, and on Japan's search for a more independent role in the world (7.45
BBC2).
Suddenly the motor car is the most popular subject for television series.
After Alexei Sayle's 'Drive' on BBC1, and before 'Tales Of Modern Motoring'
which starts later this month on BBC2, the Channel 4 culture series Without
Walls offers a three-part series called 'Carnography'. They begin today by
comparing a Ferrari with the Dodge Viper (9.00). In the second half of WW
Craig Raine defends the poet Rudyard Kipling from the politically correct
lemmings who mindlessly attack him (9.30).
Hidden under television's most forgettable umbrella title, Network First, is
a documentary about the Central School Of Ballet in London (10.40 ITV). BBC1
screens the long and inferior version of Spielberg's 1971 television drama,
Duel about a car driver (played by Dennis Weaver) who is pursued by an
articulated tanker (11.45).
</TEXT>
