<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Unions may sponsor Lib Dems
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Liberal Democrat parliamentary candidates may one day accept sponsorship
from trade unions, Mr Alex Carlile, the party's employment spokesman, said
yesterday. The party and the Trades Union Congress are to hold their first
official meeting today.
'I would not want candidates to be beholden to a union but sponsorship by
unions is certainly on the agenda,' he said.
The meeting between the two organisations follows an invitation from Mr
Paddy Ashdown, Liberal Democrat leader, but builds on several months of
informal contact.
The meeting is important to both organisations more for the signals it sends
to others, rather than for the substance of the discussion.
The TUC has shifted in the direction of the Liberal Democrats on many
industrial relations issues during the past five to 10 years.
'Ten years ago we would still have opposed strike ballots, works
council-type bodies for representing workers' views, and the European
Community - now we join the Liberal Democrats in embracing them all,' said a
TUC official.
The Liberal Democrats have won TUC approval for strongly supporting the
social dimension of the European Union and the restoration of union rights
at GCHQ, the government's communications monitoring base at Cheltenham.
Some TUC officials have even suggested that the party has better policies on
full employment and employee involvement than Labour.
But some union leaders - in particular Mr Rodney Bickerstaffe of Unison, the
public services union - have expressed reservations about an official
meeting so close to the local elections.
The TUC has impressed Liberal Democrats in its attempt to distance itself
from the Labour party. 'The organisation has been trying to de-politicise
itself and has made some progress,' Mr Carlile said.
The meeting helps the TUC's attempt to become a more politically neutral
lobby organisation for those at work. Its links with Labour have won it
little influence in the past 15 years. The TUC is also aware that about 25
per cent of its members voted Liberal Democrat at the last election.
Differences remain over such issues as the minimum wage policy and union
recognition rights, but it is in the interests of both organisations to
maintain friendly relations. A new Liberal Democrat employment policy paper,
due soon, will be closely scrutinised in Congress House.
</TEXT>
