<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Coal chief warns bidders of risk: Claim that sell-off will
cause casualties angers private-sector mining groups
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Potential bidders for British Coal were given a stark warning by the
corporation chairman yesterday that some producers seem certain to be
'squeezed from the market' after the industry's privatisation.
Mr Neil Clarke said there would be fierce competition on supply between the
buyers of the five regions of British Coal, the leasors of pits already
closed by British Coal and importers. The scope for expanding existing sales
outside the electricity supply market was only about 3m tonnes.
'This is not likely to be a war without casualties,' he told a monthly
meeting of the Coal Industry Society. 'It would seem inevitable that
ultimately some producers will be squeezed from the market.'
Mr Clarke also said that reductions in British Coal's capacity brought
supply and demand far closer to a sustainable balance. This suggests such a
balance has yet to be achieved and will reinforce fears that there will be
more closures among the 17 remaining pits before privatisation.
Mr Clarke's comments were greeted with surprise and anger by private-sector
miners. Mr Richard Budge, chief executive of RJB Mining, which has already
re-opened one pit closed by British Coal and may bid for one of the five
regions, said private-sector mines were well used to competition.
Another private-sector miner described Mr Clarke's speech as churlish. 'If
British Coal had got its costs down as it should have done the market now
would be much bigger.'
Separately, the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors said the government
would have to adopt a more commercial approach to the privatisation of
British Coal if taxpayers were to get value for money from the sale.
It criticised proposals that bidders for coal rights should pay a lump sum
rather than a royalty on each tonne of coal extracted. The institution said
that the freehold of coal and colliery land should remain with the coal
authority.
In his speech, Mr Clarke defended British Coal's marketing, saying it was
recovering business by, for example, supplying coking coal for British Steel
in south Wales. British Coal expected to maintain its market share this year
in spite of colliery closures.
Outside the electricity industry and coking coal, sales of coal in the UK
next year would be about 13m tonnes of which British Coal would supply at
least 9m tonnes. Some imports could not be displaced because of quality
factors, so the maximum scope for expanding sales would be about 3m tonnes.
Production from up to 10 pits being leased out could be more than 3m tonnes
a year, he said. Most of this is being aimed at the non-electricity and
coking coal markets.
Mr Clarke said the expansion in British Coal's range and volume of products
would continue.
</TEXT>
