<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Anti-smoking aids on NHS urged
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Anti-smoking aids should be available on National Health Service
prescriptions and some of the money raised by tobacco tax should be used for
community-based health education, the Policy Studies Institute argues in a
report published today.
The independent think-tank argues for a link between tobacco control
strategy and family welfare policy.
It says the government's policy of raising tobacco tax at twice the rate of
inflation is likely to reduce cigarette consumption among the majority but
has no effect on those least able to afford to smoke.
Smoking is greatest among the most disadvantaged families, the report says.
Nearly three-quarters of council tenants receiving means-tested benefits
smoke, spending Pounds 16 a week - or Pounds 1 in every Pounds 7 of their
net disposable income.
