<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Multimedia sewer trip offered
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A computer company is offering 'surrogate' trips into dirty, difficult and
dangerous environments as its contribution to the multimedia revolution.
The Rothwell Group of Hampshire is offering the service on standard personal
computers. The company, which has an annual turnover of more than Pounds
20m, is expanding into providing applications for business.
Under the title BeingThere, Rothwell is offering tailor-made interactive
packages costing between Pounds 30,000 and Pounds 70,000. Possibilities
include detailed visual tours around oil rigs for new employees, an
introduction to Wembley stadium for special constables, and detailed guides
to the London Underground and sewer system for emergency workers.
BeingThere, produced in a partnership with CyberGraphics, offers the user
the choice of, for example, which way to 'walk' around an oil rig, or which
piece of machinery to zoom in on.
CyberGraphics, which specialises in surrogate travel, has produced trips
around oil rigs and a destroyer for the Royal Navy as well as geographical
profiles of border areas in Germany for the British army.
The company uses a former BBC producer, Mr Don Selwyn Gilbert, whose work
includes documentaries on the Tudor ship the Mary Rose, to carry out
detailed filming before his work is turned into digital software.
Mr Mark Compton-Hall of Rothwell admitted that so far the sale of multimedia
products in the UK had been 'singularly unspectacular'.
He said the main reason was that 'suppliers have spent too much effort
demonstrating how technically clever their products are and failing to focus
on pragmatic business solutions'.
BeingThere, which so far has attracted expressions of interest rather than
sales, is the first of what Rothwell hopes will be a series of multimedia
applications for business.
