<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Rethink urged in counties review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two politics professors have called for a pause in the English local
government review due to be finished by the end of this year, because the
process is now 'fundamentally flawed'.
They say an all-party conference should discuss how to change track.
In England, the Local Government Commission is recommending that the current
two-tier structure of counties and districts be changed into all-purpose
authorities.
But Professor George Jones, of the London School of Economics, and Professor
John Stewart of Birmingham University's Institute of Local Government
Studies, argue in the Local Government Chronicle that the way ahead should
be unitary status for large towns and cities, with slight revisions to the
two-tier system of responsibilities elsewhere.
Several districts are trying to arrange mergers so that they will be big
enough for unitary status. Formal announcements have already been made on
merger proposals for Devon, Cambridgeshire and Surrey, while several other
areas must make submissions by the end of this month.
Mr Martin Easteal, chief executive of the commission, has recommended that
new unitary authorities should have populations of between 150,000 and
250,000.
</TEXT>
