FT  08 MAR 94 / Monopolies probe on Independent less likely
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Department of Trade and Industry is increasingly likely to allow the
consortium that includes Mirror Group Newspapers to take over The
Independent newspaper without a reference to the Monopolies and Mergers
Commission.
But a waiver on the grounds of economic urgency is expected to be
accompanied by conditions designed to protect the editorial independence of
The Independent and the Independent on Sunday, both owned by Newspaper
Publishing.
The consortium, which is bidding for the shares in Newspaper Publishing that
it does not already own, brings together MGN, Mr Andreas Whittam Smith and
the principal founders of the paper, and two existing shareholders, El Pas
of Spain and La Repubblica of Italy.
Meanwhile, further details emerged yesterday of the consortium agreements
and the service deal under which MGN would handle all the operations of
Newspaper Publishing apart from editorial.
The Spanish and the Italians have an agreement to vote as one on the NP
board which they will therefore control with four of the seven board seats.
MGN will operate Newspaper Publishing's bank account and have a veto over
board decisions on new lines of business such as the launch of titles.
