<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Life companies pressed over pension survey
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH and NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Leading life insurance companies have been put on the spot by a committee of
MPs about whether they took part in the survey on pension transfers that
caused widespread public concern about mis-selling.
Mr Frank Field, the Labour MP who chairs the Commons social security
committee, has written to the six largest providers of personal pensions
asking if their pensions business was included in the sample studied by
accountancy firm KPMG Peat Marwick.
If some companies now declare that they did not take part in the study, as
the Prudential has already done, attention will focus on the others.
As part of the committee's inquiry into aspects of personal and state
pensions, Mr Field has also written to the Securities and Investments Board,
the City's chief watchdog, which commissioned the study, asking what further
steps it intends to take in response to the survey.
SIB has set up an inquiry into how to ensure higher standards in the sale of
pension transfers, and is due to publish a report on that by the end of this
month. It will then turn its attention to how people who suffered as a
result of following poor advice should be compensated.
The KPMG study suggested that in only 9 per cent of cases was there evidence
of substantial compliance with the regulators' rules on selling pensions to
people transferring a lump sum out of an occupational pension scheme.
The six organisations contacted by the committee are Pearl, TSB Group,
Prudential, Legal &amp; General, Allied Dunbar and Abbey Life.
This demand for information will put greater pressure on those companies
which have been unwilling to reveal their participation in the study, even
though regulators have emphasised that the findings were representative of
the industry as a whole. At least one of those Mr Field has written to is
understood to have taken part in the survey.
</TEXT>
