<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Prejudice denied over union post at Bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Political prejudice did not motivate Mr John Major, the prime minister, in
his decision not to re-appoint a trade unionist as non-executive director of
the Bank of England, Mr Anthony Nelson, economic secretary to the Treasury,
told the Commons yesterday.
Trade unionists had never been appointed to serve a 'constituency interest',
he said.
Mr Gavin Laird, general secretary of the AEEU engineering and electrical
union, has already served two terms of office on the Bank's court of
governors.
Mr Alistair Darling, Labour spokesman on the City, attributed the prime
minister's failure to re-appoint Mr Laird to 'weakness or prejudice'. He
said it would be the first time since the Bank was nationalised in 1946 that
there would be nobody representing unions on the court of governors.
Mr Alan Beith, deputy leader of the Liberal Democrats, said the break with
the long-established practice of appointing someone from a union background
to the court of governors was widely felt to be 'undesirable'.
Mr Nelson praised Mr Laird's contribution to the Bank and insisted that no
reflection had been cast on him by the prime minister's decision. He said:
'There is no intention to be partisan in this matter. It is far too
important for party politics to play any part.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6011 Federal Reserve Banks.
</IN>
<XX>
