<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Departments battle to run jobseeker's allowance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Officials at two Whitehall departments - social security and employment -
are locked in battle over who will control the new jobseeker's allowance,
which will replace the system of unemployment benefit.
The allowance, to be introduced in April 1996, has been jointly promoted by
both departments. A final decision on which of them is to administer
payments has yet to be taken and could involve the transfer of a budget
worth several billion pounds from social security to employment.
With departments in the process of deciding what legislation they will push
to have included in the 1994-95 parliamentary session, the DSS has included
the bill introducing the allowance on its list of submissions.
But the Department of Employment is understood to be keen that it should be
the lead department in steering the bill through parliament - putting it in
pole position to administer the new allowance afterwards.
Winning the argument - described by one official recently as 'quite a scrum'
 -would have a dramatic impact on the employment department's annual budget
of Pounds 3.7bn, probably more than doubling it.
The dispute is given added piquancy because of the ministers at the heads of
the two departments involved. Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary,
and Mr David Hunt, employment secretary, come from opposite ends of the Tory
party's political spectrum.
At present, however, the row is said to be confined largely to officials.
The Budget outlined plans for unemployment benefit to be merged into a new
jobseeker's allowance. The new allowance - the level of which has not been
set - would be paid for six months, after which recipients would switch to
income support.
Under the present benefit system, most people over 18 who become unemployed
receive weekly unemployment benefit of Pounds 44.65 in the first 12 months
before switching to income support.
In 1992-93, the government spent a total of Pounds 9.3bn on the unemployed,
with a large proportion being paid out in the form of unemployment benefit
and income support.
Both unemployment benefit and income support currently come out of the
Pounds 80bn DSS budget.
It has long been accepted in Whitehall that the unemployed should be served
by one department rather than two as at present. One factor in the
employment department's favour is that the DSS's main legislative priority
is likely to be pensions reform.
</TEXT>
<XX>
