<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Companies win big share of civil service work
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The private sector has won more than three-quarters of the Pounds 1.1bn of
civil service work put out to tender so far, according to figures given to a
committee of MPs by Mr William Waldegrave, public services minister.
Private companies have won contracts worth Pounds 850m to provide a wide
range of services to the government, including estates and facilities
management, financial support and computer services.
Savings on contracting-out are running at about 23 per cent of the value of
work tested, Mr Waldegrave said. The programme is expected to have covered
Pounds 2.3bn of civil service activities by the end of September.
The figures have been submitted to the Commons Treasury and civil service
committee which will question Mr Waldegrave today. The committee is
investigating concerns over the impact of civil service reforms on the
quality of public services and probity in handling public money.
Market testing has so far put the jobs of 25,000 civil servants up for
competition. The contracts so far completed will reduce civil service
numbers by 14,500, with just over 12,000 civil servants transferring to the
private sector.
More than 7,000 of these transfers will be covered by the Tupe regulations
which preserve the pay and conditions of staff in transfers of employment.
The Cabinet Office estimates that the total cost of the market-testing
programme so far has been less than Pounds 20m. This is much lower than the
Pounds 100m the civil service unions allege has been spent.
More than 400 activities have so far been reviewed under the programme
launched with the Competing for Quality white paper. Three have been
privatised, 25 abolished and another 20 withdrawn after restructuring or
unsolvable problems were encountered.
More than 230 activities were market tested, with the staff currently doing
the job competing against outside bidders. In-house teams won 150 of these,
with the rest going to contractors.
The remaining 113 cases were put out to tender without a bid from the staff
currently doing the work. Ministers believe that departments and agencies
are increasingly following business in making strategic decisions to
withdraw from non-core activities.
Savings total Pounds 136m on the Pounds 590m of work in the programme where
firm figures are available. The figures for two large contracts - the Inland
Revenue's information technology services and the Atomic Weapons
Establishment at Aldermaston - cannot be quantified until negotiations with
contractors have been completed.
Information technology services are the largest group of activities
contracted out under the programme, affecting more than Pounds 300m of
business. These include the partnership agreement under which the Inland
Revenue will transfer its IT work to EDS-Scicon, the US contracted-services
group, in a deal worth almost Pounds 2bn over 10 years.
</TEXT>
