<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / PM sets up inquiry on Ulster talks leak
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major has launched an inquiry into how details of his private
meeting with Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, at Downing Street on
Wednesday evening were leaked to a Sunday newspaper.
The prime minister said yesterday he had put inquiries 'in hand', the talks
on tomorrow's debate for the renewal of the Prevention of Terrorism Act
'should not have been leaked'. It was important that such meetings could be
held in private, he said.
Mr Smith welcomed the move. In a letter to Mr Major which officials
described as a 'nudge' at the prime minister's elbow, the Labour leader said
he trusted the inquiry would be 'both thorough and comprehensive'.
Downing Street said the prime minister was satisfied the leak did not
emanate from Number 10 and had instructed the Home Office and the Northern
Ireland Office to hold similar inquiries.
Labour regularly votes against renewal of the act but had wanted to see if
its disagreement with the government over two specific measures could be
bridged before tomorrow's debate, timed to coincide with a vote on whether
to set up a select committee on Northern Ireland.
Mr Major told BBC radio: 'We looked very carefully at what John Smith
proposed. I decided it was not in the interests of the proper working of the
Prevention of Terrorism Act to adopt the proposals he put forward.'
Mr Dick Spring, the Irish foreign minister, said yesterday he was still
confident of resuming all-party talks on the future of Northern Ireland in
spite of unionists' repeated refusal to take part.
Mr Spring and Sir Patrick Mayhew, the Northern Ireland secretary, are to
make a more detailed assessment of the prospects for negotiations when they
jointly chair a session of the UK-Irish intergovernmental Ulster Conference
in London on Thursday.
</TEXT>
