<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Scottish poll puts Tories on 13%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Conservative party has sunk to its lowest level ever in opinion polls in
Scotland, a System Three poll in today's Herald newspaper based in Glasgow
says. The poll puts Tory support in Scotland at 13 per cent, the party's
lowest rating since since the poll began 20 years ago, James Buxton writes.
The Tories' standing is only half the 25.7 per cent it won at the 1992
general election and is three points down on its showing at the end of
January. It puts the Tories in fourth place for only the second time in the
poll's history.
Labour support is unchanged at 47 per cent while the Scottish National party
has risen three percentage points to 25 per cent. The Liberal Democrats are
unchanged at 14 per cent.
Mr Alex Salmond, SNP leader, said the poll showed the nationalists were in a
position to challenge Labour in the forthcoming local and European
elections.
News of the poll, based on interviews with 1,035 people between February 24
and March 3, came on the day Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, launched
the Conservatives' spring offensive, saying the party would fare well at the
elections.
