FT  08 MAR 94 / US grants will aid 'telecoms highway'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The US Commerce Department yesterday took a step towards a US 'information
superhighway' by announcing that Dollars 26m (Pounds 17.8m) in federal
matching grants is available for telecommunications technologies for
schools, hospitals and libraries.
Mr Ron Brown, secretary of commerce, said his department would target those
who needed help, thus avoiding pockets of 'information haves and have nots.'
The department will provide up to 50 per cent of the cost for demonstration
projects, which use diverse technologies and can serve as models for others,
and planning grants. The funds could, for example, spur 'telemedicine,'
allowing hospitals swiftly to exchange information, and 'remote learning' by
making data available to rural schools.
Mr Brown also attempted yesterday to head off a Republican assault on the
National Competitiveness Act.
The legislation funds two other Commerce Department schemes; the advanced
technology programme, allowing grants for research and development of
generic technologies, and the manufacturing extension partnership, to
disseminate manufacturing advances in the country.
Gates scorns trials, Front Page of Second Section
