FT  08 MAR 94 / French move on organised crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A leading French judge yesterday handed the justice minister a report
recommending the creation of 11 regional police squads to fight organised
crime, writes David Buchan.
Mr Thierry Jean-Pierre, a justice ministry adviser, is reported to have
criticised an inter-ministerial body, the Central Service for the Prevention
of Corruption, for not acting on a dozen cases which it should be following
up, including 'at least four concerning elected politicians and
journalists'.
The report comes as the murder of a French deputy in the south of France 10
days ago has focused attention on organised crime in the Riviera and
coincides with a parliamentary by-election in scandal-ridden Nice. After a
first round of voting at the weekend, the Gaullist mayor of Nice, Mr
Jean-Paul Barety, looks likely to win next Sunday, despite an exceptionally
strong showing by his National Front rival.
Mr Barety beat Mr Jacques Peyrat, the National Front candidate, by just 34
votes but the Socialist party is now expected to openly support Mr Barety.
