<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAR 94 / Major acts to avert leadership challenge: PM warns he will
fight to stay in office as Hurd seeks to unite party
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Major yesterday sought to pre-empt a challenge to his party
leadership later this year with a blunt warning to Tory critics that he
would fight to remain in 10 Downing Street.
In a move calculated to avert the threat of a leadership crisis after this
summer's local and European elections, the prime minister said he had a
mandate to remain in office at least until the general election due by 1997.
His comments coincided with a renewed attempt by Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign
secretary, to unite the Conservative party around a common position for the
June European elections.
In a speech echoed by the prime minister, Mr Hurd said Europe should abandon
grand ambitions for a federal structure in favour of making the present
institutions work effectively.
But amid a continuing battle within the Conservative party to shape its
manifesto for the European elections, that stance was attacked by Sir Edward
Heath, former prime minister, who said it would diminish Britain's influence
within the Union.
Mr Major's remarks followed the speculation at Westminster that Mr Michael
Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, has been positioning himself to
challenge Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, for the leadership if Mr Major
steps down.
Mr Clarke, in an interview with The Independent, made it clear that he
remained a contender for the leadership, 'but at a time of John Major's
choosing'.
Speaking on BBC Radio's Jimmy Young programme, Mr Major brushed aside
suggestions that the expected defeats for the Conservatives in the local and
European elections in May and June could force him from office.
Recalling that in 1992 the Conservatives had won more votes than any party
in UK history, he said: 'I was elected to remain prime minister of this
country at least until the next election and beyond it if I win it.'
Mr Major said talk that Mr Heseltine was poised to replace him was 'unreal'.
He declared: 'I have never run away from a challenge in my life and I'm
surely not doing so now.'
Acknowledging that he had faced constant allegations of weakness and
indecision, Mr Major insisted that he had not been shaken from his main
policy objectives: 'The things that matter are what emerges at the end of
the struggles, not what vitriol may be hurled during the time of the
struggles.'
He offered an upbeat assessment of economic prospects, emphasising that
inflation was set to remain below 3 per cent and that growth this year would
meet the Treasury's forecast of 2.5 per cent. But Mr Major was forced to
admit that the Conservatives' pre-election promises in 1992 to cut taxes had
been based on an over-optimistic assessment of the economic outlook.
Referring to the impending tax increases, he said: 'We did get it wrong. But
the important thing, having got it wrong, is not to shrink from the action
that is necessary to put the economy on the right path.'
Mr Clarke said that he did not propose to reduce taxes 'before recovery or
before we have healthier public finances'.
Mr Major accepted that the government had made a 'mistake' when in 1988 it
had briefly linked the sale of arms to Malaysia with aid provision. The
mistake had been put right, he said.
A new opinion poll in Scotland, published last night, showed the
Conservatives with the support of just 13 per cent of voters.
Hurd's speech, Page 11
Scottish poll, Page 10
Consumer credit drop signals belt-tightening, Page 13
Observer, Page 21
