<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAR 94 / Emerging Markets: News round-up
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Secondary market
A sharp collapse in the price of secondary market emerging market debt has
left many traders in the paper nursing losses.
Among prominent traders, JP Morgan, the top-ranked New York bank, saw its
shares fall last week as reports swept the market that it had lost money in
both emerging market debt and derivatives trading.
Simply holding the paper has been enough to help some traders to riches as
prices rose relentlessly over the past few years. But losses since the
market peaked in mid-January have been rapid.
An index calculated by West Merchant Bank - which includes both Brady bonds
and restructured bank loans - has fallen almost 13 per cent since it peaked
in mid-January.
Falls were sharpest in countries that have yet to achieve a Brady debt
restructuring. Russian paper lost the most as the price fell more than 40
per cent to just over 30 cents on the dollar.
Other big losers were Peru, off more than 25 per cent, Nigeria, down 22 per
cent, and Panama, down 20 per cent.
VENEZUELA
Venezuela became the first country with outstanding Brady bonds to be
downgraded when Standard &amp; Poor's lowered its ratings on the republic's
Eurobonds to double-B minus from double-B. About Dollars 2.1bn of foreign
currency-denominated debt is affected. It has revised its outlook to stable
from negative.
S &amp; P said the downgrade stemmed from a further substantial weakening in the
country's public finances in recent months and uncertain prospects that the
new government can pursue effective fiscal and economic reforms over the
medium term.
MANILA
The country's two stock exchange trading floors - in the Ortigas Centre and
the Makati financial district - began their merger by trading one stock at a
single price last Friday. It is hoped to complete the process in about two
weeks.
LONDON
The Investment Bank of Latvia has signed an equity agreement with the EBRD.
The equity stake is the first foreign participation in the bank, and
represents 35 per cent of its capital. The LIB, established in 1992, aims to
promote Latvia's economic development by lending hard currency to the
private sector. Lending goes mainly into the wood processing sector, but
also into tourism, harbour facilities and light industry.
CAIRO
Egypt is considering offering shares of some 314 public sector companies for
public subscription. The government has said that about 90 of 360 state
companies were running at a loss, with debts of about Dollars 16bn.
BRATISLAVA
Direct foreign investment to Slovakia was about Dollars 135m in 1993, down
from Dollars 151m in 1992, the Slovak statistical bureau has said. Foreign
capital investment since the communist government fell in 1989 has totalled
Dollars 366.2m.
Austria was the leading investor from 1990 to 1993 with Dollars 87m placed
in 1,141 companies. Germany followed with Dollars 77m in 743 companies. The
US has invested Dollars 47m in 161 companies, and the Czech Republic Dollars
40m in 666 companies.
Further coverage of emerging markets appears daily on the World Stock
Markets page.
</TEXT>
