<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAR 94 / Company News (This Week): An acquisitive animal faces City
unease - BTR
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Why have shares in BTR underperformed the market by about 20 per cent since
last August? That question is likely to be exercising the executives of one
of Britain's biggest and most successful international manufacturing
companies as they prepare to present the group's 1993 results on Thursday.
BTR unsettled the market by warning in September that the outlook remained
uncertain for economic recovery in the second half. Analysts duly trimmed
their forecasts and the current expectation is for pre-tax profits of about
Pounds 1.23bn, compared with Pounds 1.06bn.
But Mr Alan Jackson, chief executive, will also want to dispel some of the
less tangible unease that has been expressed about BTR. This has cited
everything from executive departures to Mr Jackson's sale in January of half
of his shares in the company.
A more long-standing issue is the extent of BTR's reliance on acquisition
accounting. This concern was revived recently by the analyst Mr Terry Smith
whose book, Accounting for Growth, has enjoyed considerable success. BTR has
used up nearly all the provisions set up when buying Hawker Siddeley, the
aerospace and engineering group, for Pounds 1.5bn in 1991.
Analysts will ask what provisions have been created for Rexnord, the US
manufacturer bought for Dollars 820m (Pounds 560m) in December. Some who
felt BTR might have overpaid for Rexnord will also be scrutinising its
likely contribution to profits. The Rexnord deal pushed gearing above 90 per
cent, but the debt level is being reduced by such cash-raising deals as this
month's Pounds 200m flotation of Graham Group, the builders merchants.
The group has hit rougher patches with the City than this. Perhaps Mr
Jackson's main task is to reassure shareholders that economic upturn will
benefit BTR as well as more obvious recovery stocks.
</TEXT>
<XX>
