<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAR 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
You could easily miss the start of what may prove to be a fascinating
exercise. At 7.58, at the end of the piano masterclass given by Jean-Bernard
Pommier in Young Musician Of The Year (7.20), BBC2 shows a two-minute
vignette in somebody's life. Inspired by the remarkable success of its
'Video Diaries' exercises, the BBC's Community Programme Unit is attempting
a 'Mass Observation type project'. This week there will be two-minute
programmes at 7.58 or 8.28 each day, and plans are being discussed for
weekly and monthly programmes with an annual review.
One of the most engrossing programmes on television, Horizon, describes the
amazing mission to repair the Hubble telescope (8.00 BBC2). C4 continues
Phil Agland's documentary account of life in a Chinese city, Beyond The
Clouds (9.00). Panorama offers one of those horrifying accounts of entire
populations suffering from atomic bomb testing, this time in Utah (9.30
BBC1). ITV begins another batch of its outstanding Memoirs Of Sherlock
Holmes with Jeremy Brett as the detective (9.00).
