<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAR 94 / Pay awards move upwards to track inflation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Annual pay awards are picking up in line with rising inflation, two reports
published yesterday say.
Figures from Industrial Relations Services show that the average settlement
for the three months to the end of January 1994 edged up to 2.5 per cent,
compared with 2 per cent in the three months to the end of December.
More than half of the settlements in the three months to January provided
increases of between 2 per cent and 2.9 per cent, contributing to the first
significant movement in the IRS headline figure since August last year.
However, only a quarter of the deals were worth more than a year earlier
and, thanks to the relatively sharp rise in inflation, the average rise has
failed to clear the rate of inflation for the first time in three years.
IRS says that with almost two-thirds of the year's pay reviews to be
completed by the end of April, the next few weeks will be of crucial
importance to pay planners. 'We may be seeing a return to a familiar pattern
 -pay pressures being driven upwards in the wake of rising prices - which
would frustrate the government's desire to break the link between pay and
inflation,' concludes IRS.
This picture is supported by rival pay analysts Incomes Data Services, which
says that settlements are mainly between 2 per cent and 3.5 per cent, and
slightly up on the end of last year.
It says that less than 10 per cent of companies are freezing pay, with a
similar proportion settling at 4 per cent or 5 per cent.
IDS adds that about a third of January settlements were higher than one year
earlier.
Pay and Benefits Bulletin 347, Industrial Relations Services, 18-20 Highbury
Place, London N5 1QP. Incomes Data Services Report 660, 193 St John Street,
London EC1V 4LS.
</TEXT>
<XX>
