<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAR 94 / Smith 'furious' at leak of Major meeting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr John Smith yesterday warned that Labour may not take part in bipartisan
meetings after a private talk with the prime minister was leaked to the
Sunday Express.
The private meeting focused on the forthcoming renewal of the Prevention of
Terrorism Act, which Labour regularly votes against.
Mr Smith wanted to see if Labour's disagreement with the government over two
specific measures of the act could be bridged before it comes up for annual
renewal on Wednesday.
The Labour leader asked for the removal of internal exclusion orders and the
provision which allows suspects to be detained for seven days before a
charge is made.
Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, yesterday said the government had
rejected the demand because such a two party 'approach would have weakened
the fight against terrorism'.
Mr Smith was reported to be 'furious' that the meeting had been made public
and called for an independent inquiry into how it had been leaked. The
meeting, which took place at 10 Downing Street, was just between Mr Smith
and Mr John Major.
The Labour leader has warned that unless he receives a satisfactory
explanation it may not be possible to have meetings on security matters. His
office accused the government of 'playing politics with Northern Ireland'.
Downing Street denied that it leaked the meeting. Mr Howard regretted the
fact that the meeting had been made public. 'These meetings were private.
They should have remained private,' he said.
However, Mr Howard was unapologetic for refusing to accept the offer of a
bipartisan approach.
He told BBC TV: 'Just as Labour supported the Prevention of Terrorism Act
until 1983 we believe it is essential in the fight against terrorism today.'
</TEXT>
