<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAR 94 / IoD warns of tax blow to business confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Confidence about economic prospects is rising but many business leaders are
worried by the prospect of next month's tax increases, an Institute of
Directors survey says today.
Mr Peter Morgan, the institute director-general, said the economic upturn
was continuing although 'muted'. He said business confidence could be
expected to dip before the tax increases, which are likely to depress
consumer spending and company order books.
The poll of 302 companies in manufacturing and services indicates that sales
volumes have risen since December although the rate of increase in orders
and profits has fallen.
According to the survey, conducted last month, 53 per cent of companies were
more optimistic about the economy than six months previously. That compared
with 47 per cent in the last survey in December, although it is well below
the 65 per cent recorded in August.
Nearly two-thirds of the companies said they were more hopeful about their
own business's prospects than six months before. Only 58 per cent gave this
answer in December. More than three-fifths of companies had increased sales
volumes, slightly above the figure at the end of last year.
The poll showed order books continuing to expand, though at a slower rate
than in December, with 57 per cent of companies reporting increased orders
last month compared with 58 per cent in December.
Profits were rising, though more slowly than last autumn, and this was a
'cause for concern', the institute said. Just over half of the companies
that responded to the poll said profits were up, compared with 55 per cent
in December last year and 57 per cent in October.
The proportion of company investment directed to what the institute calls
the 'key areas' of research and development, machinery, training and
advertising has fallen slightly since December. These declines have been
offset by increases in cash spent on acquisitions, buildings and working
capital, leaving overall investment levels unchanged.
Cashflow remained a big problem for two out of five companies while lack of
demand was rated as a serious difficulty by nearly a third. Prospects for
employment were considered slightly worse with 37 per cent of companies
saying they were likely to take on more workers compared with 39 per cent in
the December survey. Consumers are increasing borrowing, especially for cars
and other expensive items, says a report today from the Finance and Leasing
Association, which represents companies providing credit to individuals and
businesses. The association said its figures indicated that next month's tax
increases had not sapped people's enthusiasm for taking out loans, although
it was concerned about weakness in companies' investment spending.
Institute of Directors bi-monthly survey of industry trends, Director
Publications, Mountbarrow House, Elizabeth Street, London SW1W 9RB. Annual
subscription: Pounds 75 non members, Pounds 60 members.
Monthly statistics available on request from Finance and Leasing
Association, 18 Upper Grosvenor Street, London W1X 9PB.
</TEXT>
